      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Thanks to Jane Smiley (''There They Go, Bad-Mouthing Divorce Again,'' Op-Ed, Sept. 12).</p>
        <p>With regard to child-rearing, there are bad marriages and bad divorces, and good marriages and good divorces.</p>
        <p>Regardless of whether their parents are divorced or married, children react negatively to the level of parental conflict they witness, to being used as pawns in the parental battle, and to indifference and neglect. My former husband and I worked very hard at parenting well together after our divorce, just as we did while married.</p>
        <p>JOANNE ROCKLIN  Los Angeles, Sept. 12, 2000</p>
      </block>
